London Page 15
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-8031</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DHRCGAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930818
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's generally good series of sports documentaries On The Line deals today
with England's first-class cricket umpires. Who knew that after a county
match umpires are 'marked' by the team captains? With only a seasonal
contract and the sort of intimidation of umpires now practised by players,
the job looks pretty unappealing (8.30).
The penultimate offering in BBC2's season of drama repeats from the 1960s
and 70s, The Wednesday Play, is 'Hard Labour', devised by Mike Leigh, and
with a cast that includes Bernard Hill, Ben Kingsley and Alison Steadman.
(9.00). The star is Liz Smith who plays a put-upon housewife and char.
In its 'gay' season Channel 4 shows the movie The Hours And Times, an
account of an imaginary weekend in Barcelona in 1963 with John Lennon
resisting the advances of Beatles' manager Brian Epstein.
ITV pursues its fixation upon crime and punishment with a 2 1/2 hour drama
documentary about a young criminal who killed himself in Swansea prison
three years ago, 15: The Life And Death Of Philip Knight (9.00).
