<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Farmers seek to save wages board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FARMERS and their employees are fighting to save the Agricultural Wages
Board, the only remaining statutory body to set minimum pay rates for
low-paid workers.
Their campaign has persuaded Mrs Gillian Shephard, agriculture minister, to
extend the consultation period about the future of the board until November.
The deadline had been September. Mrs Shephard, as employment secretary this
year guided legislation through parliament to scrap wages councils next
month. The councils set minimum rates for 2.5m private-sector workers. But
the legislation does not cover the board, which is governed by agricultural
rather than employment regulations.
Farmers and farm workers believe the board is still relevant in an industry
where it is estimated that workers earn 76 per cent of the average male wage
and craftworkers have a minimum rate of Pounds 159 for a 39-hour week. Many
employers pay above minimum rates, but many farm workers nevertheless claim
income support.
Mr Paul Redgate, a national officer of the TGWU general union, which
absorbed the National Union of Agricultural and Allied Workers in 1982, said
free collective bargaining worked where there was a number of employees, but
most farms employed very few workers. 'It is difficult to take industrial
action against your boss who is probably working alongside you,' he said.
Mr Oliver Walston, who employs four men on his 2,000-acre farm in
Cambridgeshire and who is active in the National Farmers Union, said
'embarrassment' was a polite way of describing the anguish he would feel if
he had to negotiate with people he knew well.
</TEXT>
