<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Earlier release for economic statistics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL ECONOMIC statistics are to be released at 9.30am instead of 11.30am, the
Central Statistical Office announced yesterday.
The change, which takes place next week, was sought by the prime minister to
give the City and financial markets more time to digest the information, and
to stop the release of figures clashing with cabinet meetings.
Downing Street yesterday said that the prime minister had also argued for
the change partly to shorten the period when information was available
without being made public.
The move stemmed from a 'prime ministerial initiative that CSO were very
happy to go along with', Downing Street said. The change fitted in with the
prime minister's Citizen's Charter initiative and was 'good news for the
users of statistics'.
The CSO has already taken steps to limit access to sensitive information
ahead of release.
Statistics released by other departments, such as employment data, will
follow suit.
The new time of 9.30am is seen as a compromise between the markets, which
want information released as early as possible, and journalists and
government officials who are not in favour of an early start.
Next week's figures for new construction orders will be the first official
statistics to be released at the new time.
The old release time of 11.30am was already an improvement for the markets
on the previous time of 3.30pm.
One City analyst commented yesterday: 'This shows that the CSO is catching
up with the working day of the City, and the new release time is good news
for lunches.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
