<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Thames to launch satellite channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THAMES Television yesterday announced the launch of a new satellite and
cable television channel, called UK Living, which will start broadcasting on
September 1, Gary Mead writes.
The move extends Thames' broadcasting alliance with two of the dominant
forces in cable communications, the US companies Cox Enterprises and
Tele-Communications (TCI).
UK Living is aimed primarily at women in the 25-45 age range in the middle
and lower socio-economic groups; there are about 3.8m women who fit that
profile in the UK. It will broadcast a mix of soap operas, chat shows,
dramas and films.
The bulk of the material will come from taking previously broadcast
programmes from BBC TV and Thames TV's extensive library. A unique feature
will be the broadcasting of BBC TV programmes within a week of their first
being transmitted on the BBC network.
The shareholders of the new channel plan to develop it alongside their
existing cable and satellite channel, UK Gold, which specialises in
broadcasting library material from Thames TV and the BBC.
UK Living has Pounds 25m in funding and a Pounds 2m launch marketing budget,
contributed by Thames, TCI and Cox.
Ms Lis Howell, formerly head of programming at the breakfast commercial
television company GMTV, is in charge of creating UK Living's schedule.
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
