<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Councils spurn reforms: Lang fails to quell gerrymandering
storm over Scottish shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE organisation which represents councils in Scotland has told Mr Ian Lang,
Scottish secretary, that it will not reconsider its refusal to co-operate
with government plans to reshape local government.
Mr Charles Gray, convener of the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities
(Cosla), has told Mr Lang: 'We are not prepared to help you make the best of
a bad job.'
Cosla strongly opposes the white paper on reorganising local government
which proposes creating 28 single-tier authorities to replace the nine
regional, three island and 53 district councils. The reform also involves
taking water services out of the hands of regional and island councils and
creating three water authorities.
Cosla has argued that the present two-tier structure should be maintained
and objects to the loss of council control of water services.
The Labour-dominated body is particularly angry about the proposed
boundaries for the new councils, drawn up without the setting up of a
commission of the kind operating in England. Mr Lang has been widely accused
of gerrymandering to create Conservative-controlled councils.
The gerrymandering charge has been levelled at the intended creation of
councils in South Ayrshire, East Renfrewshire, Stirling and Berwickshire &amp;
East Lothian which could have Conservative majorities. Critics have argued
that these councils would have smaller populations than adjoining
Labour-controlled authorities.
A recent System Three opinion poll showed support in Scotland for
single-tier councils at 29 per cent in July against 46 per cent in May.
Cosla is refusing to take part in discussions with the Scottish Office on
the details of the plan, which will form a bill in the next session of
parliament. It has urged member councils to boycott discussions.
So far Lothian and Grampian regions, which are Labour-controlled, have
banned discussion with the Scottish Office. Strathclyde region, the biggest
in Scotland, has told its officials not to take part in talks. Central and
Tayside regions are also likely to ban contact with the Scottish Office.
However, Highland region, which will survive after reorganisation while the
district councils under it disappear, has said it will continue talking to
the government. Borders region is strongly opposed to the proposal that it
should lose Berwickshire, but has nevertheless decided to keep talking to
the Scottish Office.
The boycott on discussions will make it more difficult for the Scottish
Office to complete its plans. On the other hand councils will find it more
difficult to influence the final shape of the legislation if they refuse to
discuss it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
