<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Special agent licensed to listen and learn from industry:
The Bank of England official responsible for economic information-gathering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALAN WATSON takes off his glasses, cocks his head, poses a meticulously
framed question and listens intently. It is a pose he repeats hundreds of
times a year in the course of gathering information about economic
conditions from top industrialists.
Mr Watson is the most senior of nine people employed by the Bank of England
throughout Britain to form contacts with the business world. The ideas they
come up with - from a network comprising some 3,600 companies - are fed each
month to the Bank's headquarters and shared with the Treasury. Mr Watson
acts as its 'regional agent' in north-west England, taking in Greater
Manchester, and parts of Lancashire, Derbyshire, Cheshire and Staffordshire.
The head of a 60-strong Bank branch in Manchester his main task is searching
for economic insights. He combines this with arranging contacts for
companies and providing a sympathetic ear to recession-hit executives.
Reports on the 20 or so companies Mr Watson visits each month are dictated
into a tape recorder as he drives between appointments. The reports form the
basis for his seven-page study of economic conditions in the north-west sent
monthly to Mr Mike Smith, the Bank official in London who co-ordinates the
regional agents' work.
Mr Smith translates the prose of Mr Watson and the other agents into a
five-page, confidential 'national summary' of UK business conditions.
Together with the latest economic statistics and evidence from business
surveys, the summary is fed to a small group of Bank and Treasury officials
for briefing Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, on economic developments.
With the government having been wrongfooted on several occasions during the
recession about the speed of recovery, the Bank and Treasury are examining
the regional reports increasingly closely for clues as to how close Britain
is getting to sustainable growth. The Treasury, while stopping short of
establishing as wide ranging a set of company contacts as the Bank, is
trying to learn more about conditions in industry, mainly through a series
of company visits for top officials.
Much of Mr Watson's time is taken by visits to companies and lunches and
dinners with industrialists. Through such contacts he believes he finds out
about nearly all the important events at the 400 or so companies with which
he is in contact.
Mr Watson has no formal training as an economist, spending most of his
Threadneedle Street career in departments dealing with banking and
management training. But in discussions he turns his hand to conveying the
formal Bank views about such things as how much inflation is working through
the economy.
The general conclusion from his recent visits to companies - and supported
by the monthly reports from the other eight Bank agents - is that a fragile
recovery has started. Yet it could be stifled by events such as further
economic contraction in continental Europe.
A broad assessment is given by Mr Peter Foden, chairman of the
Cheshire-based ERF truckmaker: 'The economy is healthier than it was, but
it's a long way from going mad.'
Mr Watson has to work hard at keeping the confidence of the companies he
talks to. The reports he sends to the Bank's head office do not discuss
individual companies by name.
'I try to probe but not embarrass,' he says.
Mr Watson's general knowledge about the region - and his links with
commercial banking and the Treasury - are appreciated by contacts such as Mr
Peter Jones, chairman of the Emerson housebuilding group in Alderley Edge,
Cheshire. 'I use Alan as a sounding board,' says Mr Jones.
Another fan is Mr John Waldron, chairman of Kratos, a Manchester-based maker
of scientific instruments.
'He's plugged into the (business) network in the north-west and speaks his
mind clearly.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
