<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Leasing trade seeks car register
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CHANGE in the law to weaken the right of finance companies to reclaim cars
bought innocently when they are still subject to hire purchase or leasing
agreements is being sought by the finance and leasing industry itself.
Its trade organisation, the Finance and Leasing Association, has presented
proposals for the government to set up a vehicle ownership register, which
would be complementary to the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency at
Swansea. The register would be based on the manufacturer's vehicle
identification number, which the association insists is a much more reliable
identifier than the registration number.
Any finance company which did not register its interest in a vehicle would
lose its ownership right to it in the event of a subsequent unauthorised
sale to an unsuspecting third party.
On the register would be details of ownership, mileage records, reports of
theft and insurance write-offs.
The proposals coincide with publication of an association survey of members
in the motor finance sector indicating a total of 7,500 cases of theft and
fraud related to such vehicles over the past year. Mr John Brown,
association chairman, said it was likely that the reported figures 'are just
the tip of the iceberg'.
Under the association's scheme potential purchasers would be able to gain
access to information on any car by phoning the register and on payment of a
small fee. The association also wants the law changed to require
manufacturers to register all new cars under the same system.
The proposals received support from the Retail Motor Industry Federation,
which represents the retail motor trade. It said that such changes to the
law 'are long overdue and will do a great deal to reduce road
vehicle-related fraud'.
</TEXT>
