<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Audit rap for housing associations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSING associations must improve their financial and management controls if
they are to deal with the extra private-sector funds planned for them by the
government, a report by the National Audit Office warns today.
Sir John Bourn, comptroller and auditor general, also recommends extra
powers for the Housing Corporation, which distributes government grants to
the associations.
The government intends to reduce the proportion of housing association
funding which comes from government grants from 75 per cent to 55 per cent
by 1995-96. Between now and 1995-96 an estimated Pounds 2.5bn of private
finance is needed to support forecast investment by the corporation of
Pounds 5.4bn.
Sir John says this exposes the associations to greater financial risk and
questions whether sufficient controls are in place for associations to deal
with the higher borrowing requirements which will follow these grant cuts.
He says the borrowing requirements will 'place associations' financial
management systems, practices and skills under substantially greater
pressure than has been experienced so far', while 'vigorous efforts will be
required to carry forward work on enhancing their oversight and monitoring'.
Sir John also warns: 'The willingness of the private sector to meet
associations' borrowing requirements has yet to be tested at the level
required to meet planned levels of development over the next few years.'
The report, based on a detailed study of 14 associations, makes several
criticisms of their management:
Some managing committees must be strengthened. The audit office found that
six associations had had difficulty recruiting members with the necessary
expertise, particularly in the area of finance. On average, 37 per cent of
committee members were over retirement age, and in one case this figure was
69 per cent. The pay of committee members and staff is limited by law.
Internal audits must be increased. Only six of the 14 associations studied
had been visited by internal auditors, and the corporation has no national
data on how effectively internal audits have been implemented. Most of the
associations without internal audit managed a 'significant' number of
housing units (from 1,350 to 5,600), and two had been advised by the
corporation in 1988-89 to start an internal audit.
External audits often fail to receive a sufficiently swift response from
associations - in one case the auditors raised the same observation in
successive years.
Borrowing strategies are inadequate in some cases. The report found few
associations had made 'long-term assessments of the availability of adequate
security for their proposed long-term borrowings'.
The audit office also found formal inquiries into associations by the
corporation were 'exhaustive and time-consuming'. It suggests the
corporation should be allowed to intervene before completing an inquiry, and
should publish research into using inter-association comparisons as
performance indicators.
The corporation has no power to vet the accounts of associations'
unregistered subsidiaries even though its 1991 survey found 30 associations
facing potentially serious financial difficulties because of investments in
subsidiaries ranging from Pounds 10,000 to Pounds 12m.
Housing Corporation: Financial Management of Housing Associations, House of
Commons Paper 892, HMSO. Pounds 7.40.
</TEXT>
