<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Five-year plan to boost jobs drafted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government has finalised a five-year plan to fight unemployment
by reducing hiring costs while maintaining social benefits, the labour
ministry said yesterday.
Officials said the scheme would be the centrepiece of government strategy to
reduce unemployment, forecast to rise to 12.5 per cent by the end of the
year. But they would give no details before the formal announcement
tomorrow.
The plan is expected to include a timetable for the government to take over
from employers the social security charges for employees' families. The
government has already cut employers' payments for lowest paid workers and
is committed to doing away with them entirely.
The SMIC inflation-indexed minimum wage may also be modified. Many employers
and political commentators regard it as a principal cause of unemployment,
particularly among the young. The jobless rate for 18-25-year-olds is about
20 per cent, one of the highest in Europe.
</TEXT>
