<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Chance to shop around by 2002
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL household gas consumers will be able to shop around for their supplies
by the year 2002 if ministers accept the MMC's recommendation to abolish
British Gas's hold over the market.
They are likely to be bombarded with offers to supply their homes from among
more than 30 companies competing in the new deregulated market.
Packages could be as varied as mortgages. These could include long-term,
fixed-rate contracts.
Exact arrangements for the new system have still to be worked out - the
government has yet to approve the recommendations to open the household
market fully to competition. But a free market in gas might work as follows.
In March 2002, the Jones household in North London might get an offer from a
newly formed company in, say, Manchester to supply them more cheaply than
British Gas's supply business (which by then is likely to be a separate
company anyway).
The Joneses choose the package they want and sign up with the new company.
This will not involve changes to the pipes or meters in their home which
will probably continue to be administered by British Gas's distribution
business.
The new company will supply the Joneses with gas pumped through the pipeline
network which will still be owned by British Gas. They will then charge the
Joneses.
In this new world, it would even be technically possible for the Joneses to
sign up with two suppliers which offer better prices at different times of
the day. New electronic meters are being developed to measure consumption at
short intervals, and they will be fitted with radio signalling so that they
can be read from a distance.
However, daily or even weekly changes of supplier were considered extremely
unlikely by gas companies yesterday. 'Some people will shop around,' said Mr
Stephen Gutteridge, chairman of Southern Gas. 'But I would expect most
contracts will be for about a year.'
Mr Malcolm Faulkner, chairman of Northern Gas, said daily settlements of
bills would be too costly to administer. Monthly contracts were possible.
'Some people may want to sign up for long agreements if they think it will
give them a better deal,' he said. 'It would be similar to taking out a
fixed rate mortgage.'
Northern and Southern Gas are arms of the regional electricity companies and
were set up to take advantage of the likely deregulation of the gas market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
