a troy ounce, up Dollars 5 from Friday. Dealers said the rise was caused by
heavy US investment fund buying. SILVER joined in the uptrend, gaining 15.50
to 477.50 cents an ounce, but the PLATINUM market was relatively muted,
rising only Dollars 2.75 to Dollars 387.75 an ounce. At the London Metal
Exchange the COPPER market appeared to be finding support around the Dollars
1,900 level for three months metal and despite a dip to Dollars 1,898,
coinciding with a slight narrowing in cash-to-three-months premium, the
price recovered in the afternoon aided by the steady performance of copper
futures at the New York Commodity Exchange dollar weakness. The ZINC market
was again supported on dips toward Dollars 880 a tonne for the three months
position but rallies failed to attract follow-through interest, dealers
said. Manufacturer Buying interest boosted London COCOA futures, with the
December position closing Pounds 25 up at Pounds 786 a tonne.
