<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / International Company News: Profits dip but Kmart optimistic
on outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KMART, the second-biggest US retailer, reported lower post-tax profits in
the quarter to July, with core discount stores still under pressure and
losses growing on its Pace membership warehouse operation.
But the company's shares edged up Dollars  3/8 to close at Dollars 23 1/8 in
New York after Mr Joseph Antonini, chairman and chief executive, said
second-half earnings were expected to exceed last year's levels.
Renewed strength in consumer spending, good weather, and promotional
activities, had brought about an improvement, he said.
Net income for the second quarter of Dollars 102m, or 22 cents a share, was
down more than one-third from Dollars 168m, or 37 cents, a year ago.
The company, which is in the process of revamping many of its stores to
compete with the faster-growing Wal Mart, had warned at the end of June of a
likely fall in profits.
First-half net income fell to Dollars 152m, or 33 cents a share, before
special items, from Dollars 284m, or 62 cents, the year before. Sales grew
by 10 per cent, to Dollars 19.2bn.
</TEXT>
