<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Argos says Budget may kill recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARGOS chairman Mr David Donne yesterday issued a warning to Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, that any tax increases in his November Budget could
destroy the 'fragile' recovery in consumer confidence and devastate
retailers' profits.
His warning came as the catalogue retailer revealed a 39 per cent rise in
profits to Pounds 13.2m for the 24 weeks to June 19, on sales up 10.3 per
cent to Pounds 365.9m.
Mr Donne highlighted the threat posed to retailers by the decision to move
the Budget from March to November. He warned any increase in income tax or
value added tax could snuff out improvement in consumer confidence. Some
retailers make 90 per cent of their profits during the Christmas and new
year trading period.
'Relative growth in sales is getting stronger but it is slow and fragile,'
he said. 'Increasing taxes in the Budget could have a serious impact on the
all-important Christmas trading period.'
Argos said sales were on a 'gentle upward trend', and had increased
throughout the first half. Trading was still stronger in the north than in
the south of England, but the gap was narrowing.
Excluding the impact of newly opened stores, sales had increased 5.9 per
cent, but much of this was due to 'management initiatives' including
expanding the range of some of its stores and changes to its catalogues.
Argos estimated the underlying increase in consumer spending at 1.8 per
cent, against a 0.9 per cent fall in the first half of 1992, and a 1 per
cent increase in the second half.
