<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Bosnia factions agree UN control of Sarajevo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LEADERS of Bosnia's three warring factions last night agreed in
principle to place Sarajevo under temporary United Nations control in an
attempt to speed up a settlement of the 17-month conflict in the republic.
This means Sarajevo's fate is being put 'on ice' while the feuding Serbs,
Moslems and Croats negotiate a three-way carve-up of the rest of Bosnia on
ethnic lines.
The agreement, seen as a breakthrough for the international mediators, Lord
Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, came just hours after leaders of the
warring parties met at the negotiating table in Geneva for the first time in
two weeks.
Under the pact, to be finalised by a three-member committee, Sarajevo would
be demilitarised and become a virtual open city separate from the three
proposed ethnic mini-states. UN control would extend to the airport and many
of the strategic hills from which Serbs shell the city, but would not
encompass the nearby Serb stronghold of Pale.
However, the spokesman for the mediators, Mr John Mills, cautioned that many
problems still had to be resolved.
He said the committee would examine civilian policing, the setting up of a
body to liaise with the 'UN co-ordinator' and the functioning of municipal
and UN authorities. No limit has been fixed for the UN mandate, which
diplomats said would have to be agreed by the UN Security Council. 'We are
not talking about a final agreement here,' Mr Mills said. 'The devil is
always in the details.'
Lord Owen and Mr Stoltenberg earlier this month proposed such an interim
settlement for Sarajevo in an effort to prevent deep differences over the
capital delaying an overall peace package.
Sarajevo is one of the most contested issues, as the Moslem-led government
has fought to keep control while the Serbs want to partition the city.
The three-member committee will comprise Mr Momcilo Krajisnik, speaker of
the Bosnian Serb parliament, Mr Mohammed Filipovic, a Moslem politician, and
Mr Miro Lasic, a Croat member of Bosnia's collective presidency.
The agreement coincided with UN confirmation that the last Serb militiamen
had withdrawn from strategic mountains seized over a week ago. The Serb
offensive had stalled the Geneva talks and raised the prospect of Nato air
strikes to destroy artillery threatening the capital.
Earlier yesterday Mr Alija Izetbegovic, Bosnia's Moslem president, insisted
that ending the siege of Sarajevo had to be at the top of the agenda of the
latest talks. Further sessions of the talks are due today.
Italy's offer of beds, Page 2
</TEXT>
