<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's two main terrestrial channels are, to put it kindly, looking
increasingly like themed networks. To put it unkindly they look like
channels for obsessives. BBC1 begins its evening schedule with the
Australian soap opera Neighbours, offers some news and a fashion programme,
then the British soap opera EastEnders followed by three comedy repeats -
The Good Life, May To December and French And Saunders with only another
blast of news to separate them.
ITV begins with the news, then the British soap, Emmerdale, followed by five
programmes about crime with only a blast of news to separate them: Inside
Crime, 'a series investigating the problem of rising crime and meeting the
people who have possible solutions' the half-hour police drama The Bill; The
Cook Report, which promises to expose dishonesty; American television
courtroom drama She Said No, about a rape case; and the Australian soap set
in a gaol, Prisoner: Cell Block H.
Bon viveur Keith Floyd is as good as ever in Far Flung Floyd today examining
the cooking of East Malaysia.
</TEXT>
