<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Average consumer credit 'falls by 3%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS CONTINUED to pay off their debts in the second quarter of this
year, with the number of people slightly in arrears on credit repayments
falling compared with a year ago.
Infolink, the credit information group, reported that the value of an
average outstanding consumer-credit commitment was 3 per cent lower in the
second quarter than in the same period a year earlier.
The latest survey of lenders' instalment credit agreements - mainly loans on
credit cards and hire purchase agreements - found that 90.5 per cent of
instalment credit accounts were up to date. This compares with 90.2 per cent
in the corresponding period a year ago.
The average value of credit agreements in the survey was Pounds 3,500.
While the percentage of accounts in arrears for up to three months was down
on a year ago, those for more than three months rose slightly.
Mr Brian Bailey, chairman of Infolink, said: 'While consumers are more
financially stable than they were a year ago, it would appear that the
economic climate has not improved sufficiently to alleviate all consumers
from the burden of debt.'
