<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Private plans for child secure units attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT proposals to contract out secure accommodation for children
yesterday met a negative response across the private and voluntary sectors.
Group 4 Securitas, the security company which runs the Wolds prison on
Humberside for the government, said it was 'highly unlikely' to enter the
market, while leading charities in the field, including National Children's
Home, Barnardo's, and the Salvation Army, attacked the proposals and called
for their withdrawal.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, published a consultation paper
calling for secure accommodation for children placed in care or remanded by
the courts to be opened to providers other than local authorities.
Mrs Bottomley said local authorities would continue to have an 'essential'
role as providers, but that demand for the service was rising.
She added that the children involved, some with criminal records and others
with 'severe emotional problems', were 'the most difficult to help in the
care system'.
Group Four said: 'This work is particularly focused on an area where we are
not able to put forward any better expertise than that which the local
authorities have.'
Mr Tom White, chief executive of National Children's Home, said: 'NCH
continues to be strongly opposed to the introduction of secure training
centres and under no circumstances would NCH be prepared to bid to run such
centres.'
He added: 'NCH believes that the government's preoccupation with secure
accommodation is inappropriate, and that imprisoning young people reinforces
criminal behaviour.' Any secure provision should be organised to ensure
'there can be no incentive to any organisation to see an increase in
provision'.
Mr Mike Jarman, director of childcare for Barnardo's, supported this view.
He said: 'We consider this a statutory-sector responsibility, and not a
charitable task. We doubt whether the necessary competence exists within the
private sector to provide such accommodation.'
The Associations of County Councils and Metropolitan Authorities, both
Labour-controlled, criticised the proposals.
Mr Jack Bury, of the ACC's social services committee, said; 'Local
authorities are in the business of providing total care for these young
people, which is as much about rehabilitation as containment. If profit is a
priority, it is difficult to see how the private sector could offer anything
more than the latter.'
Labour described the proposals as 'a blatant bid to cover up Conservative
failure on crime'.
</TEXT>
