<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Open all hours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A week of action was launched yesterday to highlight the plight of small
grocers, who are facing increasing competition from superstores based
outside main shopping areas, Neil Buckley writes.
Independent Grocer magazine, which is leading the campaign, has written to
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, calling for a moratorium on
superstore developments, and to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary, warning that 'endless bureaucracy' is crippling small grocery
businesses. It will stage a series of special events and bring out a special
edition to illustrate the difficulties faced by small shops.
It says that tens of thousands of small grocers have closed in the past two
decades, although the sick, the elderly, the disabled, and those without
transport rely on them.
The British Independent Grocers' Association claims superstores destroy
rather than create jobs, as every job in a new superstore can cost up to
four jobs in small businesses forced to close.
Beyond the corner shop, Page 10
