<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Big energy users scorn price-reduction scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BIG INDUSTRIAL energy users yesterday scorned an initiative by the
electricity 'pool' to reduce the cost of power.
The Energy Intensive Users Group, which represents companies such as British
Steel and Imperial Chemical Industries, said it was bitterly disappointed by
the measures.
Mr Ian Blakey, the group's chairman, said: 'The benefit which the proposed
scheme would bring to the membership was estimated to be a fraction of 1 per
cent, and would barely cover the administration costs of participation.'
The pool, where electricity is traded on a wholesale basis, approved a
scheme which it said would reduce prices by an average of 1.5 per cent and
up to 3 per cent. This would enable 'demand-side bidding', where customers
could agree not to take electricity if it went above a certain price.
Mr Blakey said an alternative scheme that would have brought larger savings
had been rejected by the pool members, who consist of the leading power
generation and distribution companies.
The group intends to appeal against the pool's decision to Offer, the
electricity regulator.
</TEXT>
