<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Price war declared in travel trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOMAS COOK, the UK's third-biggest travel agency chain, yesterday fired the
opening salvo in the campaign for customers next summer, offering a 10 per
cent discount on all holidays in its new package tour brochure.
Mr Tony Bennett, Cook's director of strategic marketing, said: 'There is a
retail price war about to break out with a good chance of blood being spilt
in the next six months. We intend to be very aggressive on price.'
Last night Pickfords and Hogg Robinson said they too would be offering 10
per cent discounts on their summer 1994 overseas holidays. Mr Andrew Jones,
Pickfords marketing manager, said: 'With more buying power through (our)
larger base, it is Thomas Cook's blood which will be spilled.'
Lunn Poly, the UK's biggest travel agent, will unveil its new brochure on
Thursday. Today Thomson, the market leader among tour operators, launches
its 1994 brochure, followed by Owners Abroad next week.
Mr Bennett said competition in the industry had been increased by
consolidation. In the past year tour operator Airtours has bought Pickfords
and Hogg Robinson, and Thomas Cook has taken a 20 per cent stake in Owners.
In addition to its opening discount offer - due to run for only a few weeks
 -Cook is continuing a promise to match any other lower price offered by a
rival chain.
This summer's top destinations are predicted to be favourites again next
year. Spain, Portugal and Turkey head the list. Cook also expects France to
be popular.
The group, which is controlled by Westdeutsche Landesbank, expects the
package holiday market to grow by 10 per cent next year, equivalent to an
extra 1m passengers.
The gradual growth in self-catering is expected to continue. Ten years ago
the self-catering market accounted for about 15 per cent of package
holidays. This year it reached 43 per cent and Cook expects it to rise to 50
per cent next year.
As part of the link with Owners, Cook will market the Enterprise holiday
brand as its own. It expects to sell between 50,000 and 100,000 Enterprise
holidays next year.
Mr Bennett said the winners of the price war were the consumers, but at some
cost. 'Discounting is against the consumer interest in the long term because
travel agents and operators alike are unable to make the investments that
will ensure improving quality.'
Owners will also use the launch of its 1994 brochure to try to revive its
fortunes. The company recently issued a profits warning to shareholders.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
