<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Watchdog weighs 'green' costs for industry: Pollution
Inspectorate chief David Slater talks to David Lascelles about his tricky
task
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID SLATER, director of the Pollution Inspectorate, has launched a
study of the costs and benefits of environmental regulation. This is to
bring 'more transparency', he says, to an issue which always triggers strong
public emotions.
He also thinks it will help Britain to avoid the excessively rigid
environmental regulation he sees in some Continental countries.
Events this year have shown just how strong those emotions can be. Two weeks
ago his inspectorate came under attack for authorising two power stations to
burn orimulsion, the 'filthy fuel' decried by environmentalists.
A few weeks earlier he caused a similar storm when he approved an
authorisation for Thorp, the nuclear waste processing plant in Cumbria,
although on that occasion ministers decided that more consultation was
needed. At the start of this year the inspectorate set emission limits for
power stations which were denounced by critics as a sell-out to the
electricity industry.
More controversy is likely as the inspectorate nears a decision to authorise
Britain's latest nuclear power station, Sizewell B, for which consultations
started last week.
Given the nature of the job it is hardly surprising that Mr Slater finds
himself amid conflicting pressures, from business, politicians and
environmental pressure groups.
He has experienced pollution at close quarters. A consultant engineer by
background, he has worked on a number of industrial disasters including
Flixborough, Seveso in Italy, Bhopal in India and Exxon Valdez in North
America.
He took on the job in 1991, shortly after the enactment of the Environmental
Protection Act, which he is responsible for implementing. He describes it as
'a sophisticated piece of legislation' which allows him room for manoeuvre.
'We don't have the radar gun approach of some of the Continental countries.
Here people can sit down and talk about the realities rather than being told
'thou shalt . . .' '
Mr Slater also has to deal with his political masters - in this case Mr John
Gummer, the environment secretary. There have been suggestions that the
politicians have been trying to get him to soften his approach because of
the fragility of the economy, for example by easing the pressure on power
stations. Yet he says they respect his independence.
The fact that the environment is a less pressing political priority than it
used to be might be thought to weaken his position. Mr Slater takes comfort
from the fact that the environment has become one of several issues that
have to be weighed, rather than the clear number one priority. He believes
this is more likely to produce a balanced result.
One of Mr Slater's concerns is to weigh the cost and benefits of pollution
controls. The recent orimulsion case was fairly clear cut. Tests showed that
the fuel was, on balance, no dirtier than coal or fuel oil, so there was no
case for banning it on environmental grounds.
Less clear, however, was Mr Slater's reason for allowing the stations to
burn the fuel for five years without clean-up equipment. His reply is that
it was 'unreasonable' to ask the generators to install this equipment
immediately, but he will maintain a dialogue with the generators to ensure
that the equipment is ready once the five years are up.
He uses words such as 'proportionate', 'selective' and 'tractable' to
describe the sort of environmental regime he wants to create. There is no
point in forcing companies to spend vast sums of money to achieve marginal
improvements in emission levels, he says. In any case the Environmental
Protection Act requires the inspectorate to follow the principle of 'best
available techniques not entailing excessive cost'.
He says: 'We're not in the business of putting business out of business.'
Nor does he like to wield a big stick, such as the threat of cancelling
licences. 'We want to get into long-term dialogue with companies and build
confidence.'
Although environmentalists accuse him of being soft on polluting industries,
he spends much of his time trying to persuade industry of the value of
environmental regulation. 'Regulatory pressure, done the right way and with
intelligence, can do good. It encourages the survival of the fittest. It can
force a company to be aware of what it's doing and of its impact.'
He likes to cite examples of companies that achieved large cost savings
after being forced to tighten up their waste and emissions. One study
project which he supported in the Aire and Calder valleys in the Yorkshire
area recruited 11 companies, each of which was able to identify worthwhile
savings by cleaning up its operations. One of them, Coca-Cola &amp; Schweppes
Beverage, produced annual savings of Pounds 1.6m.
It is a question of lining up environmental, efficiency and economic
objectives so that they all aim towards the same goal.
'It's all basically about eliminating waste,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>RES  Pollution.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
