<DATE>930817
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / AT&amp;T plans merger with McCaw: Proposed Dollars 12.3bn
telecommunications deal is one of biggest takeovers in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Telephone &amp; Telegraph announced plans yesterday for a full-scale
merger with McCaw Cellular Communications in one of the US's biggest
takeover deals valued at Dollars 12.3bn (Pounds 8.2bn).
The all-share merger will bind the largest long-distance telecommunications
company in the US to the nation's biggest operator in the cellular telephone
market.
The deal replaces an earlier scheme, announced in November, for AT&amp;T to
acquire a one-third interest in McCaw, based in Kirkland, Washington. The
proposed merger would be the largest in a series of multi-billion dollar
transactions within the telecommunications sector recently - including a
Dollars 5.3bn tie-up between British Telecom and MCI, and US West's Dollars
2.5bn investment in Time Warner Entertainment.
BT, which had previously agreed to sell its 35.8m shares in McCaw - a 17 per
cent stake - to AT&amp;T for Dollars 1.75bn, will now receive an equivalent
number of shares in AT&amp;T instead, valued yesterday at Dollars 2.2bn. BT said
it still intended to sell its stake when the deal was completed.
In New York, AT&amp;T and McCaw said the merger agreement was an 'outgrowth of
discussions' held in the wake of the proposed share stake arrangement.
Mr Robert Allen, chairman of AT&amp;T, said the full merger would be 'a better
financial deal for AT&amp;T. If we were right strategically and added value to
McCaw (under the share stake arrangement), we'd have to pay for it later'.
Nevertheless, McCaw - an entrepreneurial company which has grown quickly in
the past decade from humble beginnings under its founder, Mr Craig McCaw -
is currently loss-making, and carries long-term debt of Dollars 4.9bn. AT&amp;T
expects to see earnings dilution of about 10 per cent in 1994, when the
merger is likely to be completed, but says there will be substantial
enhancement in the long term.
When the proposed share stake arrangement was announced, the partnership was
seen as putting AT&amp;T in direct competition with the regional Bell telephone
companies for the first time since the Bell system was broken up by court
order in 1984. Aside from McCaw, the wireless communications market is
dominated by large local telephone companies and GTE.
Mr Allen said: 'AT&amp;T is not interested in re-entering the local telephone
business and today's announcement doesn't change that. More than 99 per cent
of all cellular calls go through the local telephone companies.'
The deal is conditional on a go-ahead from various regulatory agencies -
including the Justice Department, which will look at anti-trust
considerations, and both the Federal Communications Commission and certain
state regulatory bodies, which must approve licence transfers.
Last night, Mr James Young, general counsel for Bell Atlantic, one of the
'Baby Bells', said the proposed merger raised 'serious competitive issues'.
The court agreement which broke up the old AT&amp;T, 'is being used by AT&amp;T as a
competitive weapon to keep their potentially strongest competitors out of
the market', he claimed. 'We and the other regional companies must be
allowed to compete equally with AT&amp;T or any other company anywhere in the
nation.'
The FCC said the proposed merger had 'great future potential' but it would
be 'open-minded on any valid opposition'. Assuming the deal goes ahead,
holders of both McCaw's 'A' and 'B' shares will receive one AT&amp;T share for
each McCaw share held. McCaw shareholders will end up owning around 14 per
cent of AT&amp;T.
On Wall Street, AT&amp;T shares slipped Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 60 3/4 at the
close of trading while McCaw gained Dollars 5 to Dollars 56 1/4 .
Later in the day, Standard &amp; Poor's, one of the large US rating agencies,
said it was retaining AT&amp;T's long-term debt and commercial paper on
'creditwatch' for a possible downgrade. But it noted that the key regulatory
issues would not be resolved for at least six months.
