<HEADLINE>
FT  17 AUG 93 / Retail sales register strongest growth in three years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and STEPHANIE FLANDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAIL sales rose in July for the seventh consecutive month, registering
their strongest growth for more than three years, according to a
Confederation of British Industry survey published today.
The CBI's latest distributive trades survey shows that for the first time
since 1990, more companies are indicating that sales are above average,
rather than below, for the time of year.
The news may point to a consumer-led recovery, particularly after a string
of figures last week suggested growth in the manufacturing sector was
slowing.
But Mr Andrew Sentance, the CBI's director of economic affairs, said the
improvement in sales suggested 'steady growth rather than a consumer boom.
Even now, fewer than one in four retailers considers trading conditions to
be good'.
The improvement has not yet benefited retailers of all sizes, according to
Mr Sudhir Junankar, an economist at the CBI.
'Retailers with only one outlet were still reporting that trade was lower
than a year earlier,' he said. 'This indicates that the steady monthly
growth in retail sales has not yet extended to all corners of the high
street.'
The CBI said the pick-up in retail spending was filtering through only
slowly to the rest of the economy. Retailers still consider stock levels to
be too high and orders placed with suppliers are growing at a much slower
rate than sales.
Official figures from the Central Statistical Office show retail sales to be
growing at an annualised rate of 3.1 per cent. Growth has been above 3 per
cent since March.
Car sales rose modestly in July after two months of year-on-year decline,
and orders for cars have risen sharply. There was a build up in stock levels
among wholesalers.
Overseas receipts of UK financial institutions jumped a net 19.8 per cent
last year from Pounds 15.7bn in 1991 to Pounds 18.8bn, British Invisibles, a
trade group, reported yesterday.
Nearly all sectors achieved improvements in overseas earnings, with
increased earnings from overseas portfolio investments fuelling much of the
rise. These were boosted by September's devaluation of the pound.
Overseas earnings from insurance institutions were particularly strong,
jumping by 21.6 per cent to Pounds 4.3bn and taking net overseas receipts
back to levels of 1987.
UK's very tangible benefits of invisibles, Page 6
Details, Page 8
Lex, Page 16
</TEXT>
