<DATE>930816
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / Paribas sets up unit for derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANQUE Paribas, the French bank, plans to set up a new unit to guarantee its
derivatives business. It will be the first separately capitalised
derivatives unit created by a European bank, following a trend started by
Merrill Lynch and Salomon Brothers.
Financial institutions with weak credit ratings have found themselves at a
competitive disadvantage to top-rated banks in the highly credit-sensitive
but lucrative derivatives market. The crunch comes when their ratings fall
to single-A, as many firms are limited by internal restrictions to dealing
with credits rated double-A and above. Banque Paribas is rated A1 by Moody's
and A by Standard &amp; Poor's. S&amp;P assigned the new unit a preliminary rating
of triple-A on Friday.
Credit quality is particularly significant in the Dollars 4,000bn (Pounds
2,600bn) over-the-counter market in swaps and options, because exposure to a
counterparty is often over a long period.
The new Paribas unit, Paribas Derives Garantis SNC, is 99.9 per cent owned
by Compagnie Financiere de Paribas. The unit will act as a guarantor, rather
than a counterparty. Paribas said the structure had been chosen to allow
clients to continue to deal with Banque Paribas, a regulated bank. The
Commission Bancaire, the French bank regulator, has approved the structure.
The initial amount of capital backing the unit is FFr800m (Pounds 90.5m).
The total capital will be adjusted regularly according to the commitments of
PDG.
</TEXT>
