<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 93 / UK minister wants world social charter on employment rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DAVID HUNT, the employment secretary, has called for a world social
charter of minimum employment rights to supersede the European Community's
own social chapter.
Mr Hunt, who proposed the idea privately to Mr Padraig Flynn, the EC social
affairs commissioner, said it was 'ludicrous' for EC countries to introduce
extra non-wage labour costs through the EC social chapter when they had to
compete in world markets.
But he also believed there is a case for some basic level of employment
protection which all countries, including developing countries, would have
to observe.
'Instead of imposing costs on ourselves we would be better served pursuing
the idea of a world social charter,' he said.
'I would like to see such a charter concentrating particularly on basic
health and safety standards.'
Although improved world labour regulation is under scrutiny in several
countries which fear the competitive threat from low-wage south-east Asian
countries, the idea of a world social charter is unlikely to find favour
with all Mr Hunt's cabinet colleagues.
The idea, which is sometimes proposed in the form of a social clause in the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, has been discussed in France and
even the US, but is usually pushed hardest by international trade union
bodies.
On the wider issue of Europe, Mr Hunt said few of the divisions in the
Conservative party over Maastricht were a result of hard policy differences.
There is now, he said, 'a great deal to unite around on Europe'.
He will have pleased his more orthodox colleagues by stressing his support
for the government's opt-out from the social chapter of the Maastricht
treaty and by pledging to resist any imposition of EC employment directives
through the back door.
He also wants a competitiveness test to be applied to all new EC measures
and says other EC countries are now far more willing to accept such British
initiatives.
Mr Hunt also hinted that he would not be seeking another round of employment
laws to follow the latest tranche of legislation. 'In the meetings I have
had with unions and employers' organisations, the message that comes across
is that there should be time for reflection and consolidation,' he said.
</TEXT>
